🎯 Requirement

Create a User class
If someone calls a method that does NOT exist
It should print: "This method is not present"

✅ Basic Solution — Using method_missing

In Ruby, whenever you call a method that doesn’t exist, Ruby internally calls:

method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)

So we override it.

🧠 Implementation
class User
  def initialize(name)
    @name = name
  end

  def greet
    "Hello #{@name}"
  end

  def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
    puts "This method is not present"
  end
end
🔎 Test It
user = User.new("Shubham")

user.greet
# => "Hello Shubham"

user.age
# => This method is not present

When age is not found:
Ruby calls method_missing.

🚨 But Interviewers Want More

Good Ruby practice says:

If you override method_missing,
you should also override:

respond_to_missing?

Otherwise this breaks:

user.respond_to?(:age)  # should return false
✅ Proper Interview-Level Answer
class User
  def initialize(name)
    @name = name
  end

  def greet
    "Hello #{@name}"
  end

  def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
    puts "This method is not present"
  end

  def respond_to_missing?(method_name, include_private = false)
    false
  end
end
🧠 Why respond_to_missing??

Ruby uses it internally when:

Calling respond_to?

Using reflection

Rails meta-programming

JSON serialization

ActiveRecord dynamic methods

If you skip it, your object behaves incorrectly.

🔥 Bonus — Slightly Better Version

Sometimes interviewer wants to still allow super.

Better version:

class User
  def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
    if respond_to?(method_name)
      super
    else
      puts "This method is not present"
    end
  end

  def respond_to_missing?(method_name, include_private = false)
    false
  end
end
🎯 Interview Tip

After writing this, say:

"In real production code, I would call super inside method_missing unless I intentionally want to swallow the error."

That shows maturity.

💡 Even Better (Production Safe Version)
def method_missing(method_name, *args, &block)
  puts "This method '#{method_name}' is not present"
end

Shows the missing method name.

